00:00:31.200 --> 00:00:36.840
Using a combination of high-res photography, LiDAR, aerial surveillance, and 3D modeling,

00:00:36.840 --> 00:00:40.194
it's their job to monitor rockfalls in the park,

00:00:40.200 --> 00:00:45.740
which is critical,  especially when five million visitors pass through Yosemite each year.

00:00:45.740 --> 00:00:51.740
GREG: I do think that Yosemite is tailor-made for rockfalls, because the cliffs are gigantic.

00:00:51.740 --> 00:00:54.900
One example would be a rockfall in 1996

00:00:54.900 --> 00:01:00.560
where a big chunk of rock free fell most of the 3,000 feet down to the valley floor,

00:01:00.560 --> 00:01:05.760
and when it hit as an in-tact block, it generated
category five hurricane strength winds

00:01:05.760 --> 00:01:09.440
and that blew over a thousand trees
in a matter of seconds.

00:01:12.320 --> 00:01:16.780
So what happened in those final moments to cause the rock to leave the cliff?

00:01:16.780 --> 00:01:23.040
GREG: We know that there are probably decades,
