Roots can grow into these cracks and the roots will expand and push the rocks off,

00:01:33.160 --> 00:01:36.740
when water freezes in the cracks,
that can also push them off.

00:01:36.740 --> 00:01:41.800
However, roughly a third of the rockfalls in Yosemite happen at times when Greg and Brian

00:01:41.800 --> 00:01:43.900
aren't able to identify a trigger.

00:01:44.440 --> 00:01:49.200
Historically,  rockfalls were only recorded 
if they had been witnessed by humans.

00:01:49.200 --> 00:01:54.100
So to be able to track and learn from events that may happen when no one is around,

00:01:54.100 --> 00:01:56.920
Greg and Brian use a host of other tools.

00:01:59.180 --> 00:02:03.380
BRIAN: One of those tools is ground-based laser scanning, or it's also called terrestrial LiDAR.

00:02:03.380 --> 00:02:08.360
This basically gives us just millions and millions of points that we can create a three-dimensional model

00:02:08.360 --> 00:02:13.280
of the cliff. So we use high-resolution photography a lot of times. You can use these photos

00:02:13.280 --> 00:02:19.100
to zoom in very carefully on different aspects
of the wall, for trying to identify

00:02:19.100 --> 00:02:23.200
what part of the rockfall was active recently.

00:02:24.740 --> 00:02:30.320
In addition, Greg and Brian identify hazard areas 
where rockfalls have happened before.

00:02:30.320 --> 00:02:36.140
