00:03:12.429 --> 00:03:16.320
it is difficult to predict when a rockfall will happen.

00:03:16.320 --> 00:03:19.100
Varying weather conditions, quakes, and even wildlife

00:03:19.100 --> 00:03:24.880
can be the difference between a crack remaining stable for a hundred years, and a major rockfall event.

00:03:24.880 --> 00:03:29.020
BRIAN: We put in specialized gear called crackmeters behind the cracks,

00:03:29.020 --> 00:03:32.800
and they measured how much the crack would open over the course of a day.

00:03:32.800 --> 00:03:37.260
And we tracked this over three and a half years; what we found was that during periods of heating

00:03:37.260 --> 00:03:39.900
the crack would move in and out every day.

00:03:40.360 --> 00:03:45.400
Greg and Brian's research confirmed something rock climbers and geologists have hypothesized,

00:03:45.400 --> 00:03:49.220
but never proved: that rockfalls could be triggered
from hot weather.

00:03:49.220 --> 00:03:52.520
GREG: Even though we've identified heat now as a probable trigger,

00:03:52.520 --> 00:03:55.680
is the most important thing how hot it was that day?

00:03:55.680 --> 00:04:02.180
Or is it the fact that maybe it was really cold the day before, and then hot that day? We don't really know that.

00:04:03.800 --> 00:04:09.421
Despite the unknowns, Greg and Brian's research is highly valued by scientists that study mountains

00:04:09.421 --> 00:04:14.100
in Switzerland and Brazil. That's because the team
have a unique opportunity

00:04:14.100 --> 00:04:19.780
to amass a huge volume of data based on the number of rockfalls in Yosemite.

00:04:19.780 --> 00:04:25.668
There are rockfall deposits here in Yosemite that are way bigger than anything that we've seen happen

00:04:25.668 --> 00:04:31.300
in the last 150 years. Which means that there's potential for rockfalls to happen in the future

00:04:31.300 --> 00:04:35.680
that are much, much bigger  than what what we have seen historically.

00:04:36.820 --> 00:04:40.200
Which is why Greg and Brian's work is so important.

00:04:40.210 --> 00:04:45.159
It's their data that helps to keep millions of Yosemite visitors safe each year.

